{{Orphan|date=March 2014}}
'''Deb Vanasse''' (born September 12, 1957) is an American writer of more than a dozen books, many of which are set in [[Alaska]]. Her children's books include six picture books and two young adult novels. She and young-adult novelist [[Gail Giles]] are the co-authors of ''No Returns'', Book One in a planned series, the Battleband Saga. Her books for adults include ''Cold Spell'' and a forthcoming biography of the Klondike gold rush figure [[Kate Carmack]].<ref name=ADN>{{cite news |last=Dunham |first=Mike |title=Discovering Shaaw Tlaa |url=http://www.adn.com/2014/01/03/3257458/writer-hopes-to-set-record-straight.html |accessdate=6 February 2014 |newspaper=[[Anchorage Daily News]] |date=3 January 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140210035049/http://www.adn.com/2014/01/03/3257458/writer-hopes-to-set-record-straight.html |archivedate=10 February 2014 |df= }}</ref> She has also authored three travel guides on Alaska, one under a pseudonym,{{clarify|date=August 2014}} and she has edited a collection of historic photographs.
== Life and career ==
Vanasse was born in [[St. Paul, Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Gale Reference Team|title=Biography - Vanasse, Deb (1957-)|journal=Contemporary Authors Online|url=https://www.amazon.com/Biography-Vanasse-Contemporary-Authors-Online/dp/B000RYAI6U/ref=sr_1_17?ie=UTF8&qid=1394405766&sr=8-17&keywords=deb+vanasse}}</ref> Her maiden name is Debra Lynn Lehmann; her brother is the writer Chris Lehmann.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}} She lived in Ann Arbor, Michigan; Galesburg, Illinois; and Madison, Wisconsin before moving to Iowa, where she graduated from Davenport West High School. She attended [[Washington University]] in St. Louis and graduated with a Bachelor in Science from [[Bemidji State University]] in Minnesota and a Masters in the Humanities from [[California State University Dominguez Hills]].
Vanasse's debut novel for young adults, ''A Distant Enemy'',<ref>{{cite journal|last=Devereaux|first=Elizabeth|title=Review: A Distant Enemy|journal=Publisher's Weekly|date=Jan 13, 1997|volume=244|issue=2|page=76|url=http://pdc-connection.ebscohost.com/c/book-reviews/9701190720/forecasts-childrens-books|accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref> was a [[Junior Literary Guild]] selection and is featured in Best Books for Young Teen Readers, Grades 7 to 10,<ref>{{cite book|last=Gillespie|first=John|title=Best Books for Young Teen Readers, Grades 7 to 10|year=2000|publisher=RR Bowker|isbn=9780835242646|pages=1066}}</ref> as was her second novel ''Out of the Wilderness''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Carton|first=Debbie|title=Book Review: Out of the Wilderness|journal=Booklist|date=March 1999|volume=95|issue=14|page=130|url=http://pdc-connection.ebscohost.com/c/book-reviews/1887710/books-youth-books-middle-readers|accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref> Her picture book titles include ''Under Alaska's Midnight Sun'' (illustrated by Jeremiah Tramell);<ref>{{cite journal|last=Harac|first=Lani|title=What's New|journal=Teacher Magazine|date=Oct 2005|volume=17|issue=2|page=60|url=http://pdc-connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/18550888/whats-new|accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=McKay|first=Carol|title=Review: Under Alaska's Midnight Sun|journal=School Library Journal|date=August 2005|volume=51|issue=8|page=107|url=http://pdc-connection.ebscohost.com/c/book-reviews/17853730/under-alaskas-midnight-sun|accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref> ''Alaska Animal Babies'' (photographs by Gavriel Jecan); ''[http://www.totemtale.blogspot.com Totem Tale]''<ref>{{cite book|last=Lamont|first=Blanche|title=Mentoring Young Writers|year=2008|publisher=Rainbow Literacy|isbn=978-0981023809|pages=30–236|url=https://www.amazon.com/Mentoring-Young-Writers-Blanche-Lamont/dp/0981023800/ref=sr_1_25?ie=UTF8&qid=1394406100&sr=8-25&keywords=deb+vanasse}}</ref> (illustrated by Erik Brooks); and ''Amazing Alaska'' (illustrated by Karen E. Lewis). Set in a [[Yup'ik]] village, there is also a Yup'ik language edition of ''Lucy's Dance'', illustrated by Nancy Slagle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alaska.edu/uapress/browse/search/index.xml|publisher=University of Alaska Press|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> ''Black Wolf of the Glacier'', also illustrated by Nancy Slagle, is based on the true story of Romeo, a well-known wolf that lived near [[Mendenhall Glacier]] in [[Juneau, Alaska]]. ''No Returns'', Book One of the Battleband Saga, is Vanasse’s first co-authored novel with Gail Giles. ''Cold Spell'', her first work of literary fiction for adults, is part of the University of Alaska Press Alaska Literary Series.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alaska Literary Series|url=http://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/series/UAP-ALS.html|publisher=[[University of Chicago]]|accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref> Vanasse and another writer, Andromeda Romano-Lax, founded the [http://www.49writingcenter.org 49 Alaska Writing Center].<ref name="web page">{{cite web|url=http://www.49writingcenter.org/About%20Us/mission.php|publisher=49 Alaska Writing Center|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> She lives on Hiland Mountain in [[Eagle River, Alaska]], with her husband and dog.
