The '''Lensch-Cunow-Haenisch group''' was a political faction within the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]] founded in 1915 by [[Revisionism_(Marxism)#19th_century|anti-revisionist]] marxists who despite previously opposing participation in the [[First World War]] now supported it. Its name comes from the three principal protagonists: [[Paul Lensch]], [[Heinrich Cunow]] and [[Konrad Haenisch]]. They followed the initiative of [[Parvus]] in advocating a German victory as a positive step for [[social democracy|international social democracy]]. They mobilised Marxist arguments behind the war effort.<ref name="Macnair">{{cite book |last1=Macnair |first1=Mike |title=Kautsky on Colonialism |publisher=Lulu.com |isbn=9781291329810 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=OUCrBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA33&dq=Lensch-Cunow-Haenisch+group&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjDg_qqkPfbAhVBW8AKHdHDAm0Q6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=Lensch-Cunow-Haenisch%20group&f=false |accessdate=28 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

