{{short description|Third period of the Paleoproterozoic Era}}
{{geological period|timeline=off|image =|caption=Map of Orosirian
}}
[[File:Vredefort Dome STS51I-33-56AA.jpg|thumb|[[Vredefort crater]] is believed to have formed in this period]]

The '''Orosirian Period''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|ˌ|ɒr|oʊ-|ˈ|s|ɪər|i|ən}}; {{lang-el|ὀροσειρά|translit=oroseirá}}, meaning "mountain range") is the third [[geologic]] [[geologic period|period]] in the [[Paleoproterozoic]] [[era (geology)|Era]] and lasted from {{Period start|Orosirian}} [[annum|Mya]] to {{Period start|Statherian}} Mya (million years ago).<ref name="HuddartStott2013">{{cite book|author1=David Huddart|author2=Tim Stott|title=Earth Environments: Past, Present and Future|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_64G6cYuz3AC&pg=PT1599|date=16 April 2013|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-68812-0|pages=1599–}}</ref> Instead of being based on [[stratigraphy]], these dates are defined [[Absolute dating|chronometrically]].

The later half of the period was an episode of intensive [[orogeny]] on virtually all [[continent]]s.

Two of the largest known [[impact event]]s on Earth occurred during the Orosirian. At the very beginning of the period, 2023 Mya, a large [[asteroid]] collision created the [[Vredefort crater|Vredefort]] impact structure. The event that created the [[Sudbury Basin]] structure occurred near the end of the period, 1850 Mya.

For the time period from about 2060 to 1780 Mya, an alternative period based on stratigraphy rather than chronometry, named the '''Columbian''', was suggested in the geological timescale review 2012 edited by Gradstein et al.,<ref name="Gradstein_et_al_2012">{{cite book | title=The Geologic Time Scale 2012 | publisher=Elsevier | author=Gradstein, F.M. et al. (editors) | year=2012 | | volume=1 | pages=361–365 | isbn=978-0-44-459390-0}}</ref> but {{As of|2017|02|lc=y}}, this has not yet been officially adopted by the [[IUGS]].

== Paleogeography ==
The [[supercontinent]] [[Columbia (supercontinent)|Columbia]] formed at the end of this period.

